    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-10-30T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-10-30T09:00:00-05:00" n="187"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d187">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/915</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GSU1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-10-30T15:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 30, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 31, 1.10 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1509. Since I felt certain it would be in harmony with the Department’s ideas, I
                    have ventured to telegraph as follows to the Embassy at Petrograd: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>October 27, 4 p.m. According to information received Germany is keen to
                            make a separate peace with Russia, if only a temporary one, of
                            sufficient duration, it is frankly said, for the exchange of prisoners
                            after which she is indifferent as to Russia’s attitude. Her present
                            intention is undoubtedly to make Russia pay for [what] she and her
                            allies may lose elsewhere.</p>
                        <p>The Red Cross Conference between Russia, Rumania and the Central powers,
                            now in progress here, is being used to cover the exchange of officers on
                            various pretexts in case a temporary peace should not be arranged. The
                            subject of a peace has been broached in the conference but it is mere
                            discussion, not [authorized] at least not openly.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Does the Department desire that we should send them cipher copies of the
                    Legation’s telegrams to the Department relative to the conference?</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
